   143	6-value set. The coercion (a) preserves the partition_key
   144	utility for the AC-013 fixture rows (they aggregate under a real
   145	source_type bucket the corpus-build work will also populate),
   146	(b) avoids any test churn — the fixture continues to write
   147	`kind="doc"`; only the resolved `source_type` differs, (c)
   148	matches what `CORPUS-1` (CNN/DailyMail acquisition, commit
   149	`27ab8df`) will land as the production article source. The
   150	coercion is writer-internal; the canonical `kind` value is
   151	preserved verbatim in the `kind` metadata column (and in
   152	`_fathomdb_vector_rows`), so any consumer needing to distinguish
   153	fixture rows from corpus rows can still do so by reading `kind`.
   154	
   155	Rejected alternatives:
   156	
   157	- "Add `doc` as a 7th `source_type` value" — extends the
   158	  HITL-locked vocabulary without authorization. This was the
   159	  original draft and is the blocking finding in the codex
   160	  verdict (`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-review-20260527T132959Z.md`
   161	  finding 1).
   162	- "Rename the fixture kind from `doc` to one of the 6 locked
   163	  values" — touches every test that reads the AC-013 fixture
   164	  (larger blast radius than a writer-side coercion).
   165	- "Leave `source_type` nullable for unmapped kinds" — loses the
   166	  partition_key benefit for the AC-013 fixture and breaks the
   167	  "partition_key is locked" guarantee in HITL Q5.
   168	
   169	Citation: HITL lock at
   170	`dev/plans/0.7.0-HITL-recommendations.md:135-137` (vocabulary +
   171	"supersedes the `kind` default in the Pack 1 handoff").
   172	
   173	The mapping is implemented in a single Rust helper:
   174	
   175	```rust
   176	fn resolve_source_type(kind: &str) -> Result<&'static str, EngineError> {
   177	    Ok(match kind {
   178	        "email" => "email",
   179	        "article" => "article",
   180	        "paper" => "paper",
   181	        "meeting" => "meeting",
   182	        "note" => "note",
   183	        "todo" => "todo",
   184	        // Synthetic AC-013 test fixture; coerced to "article" so
   185	        // the 6-value HITL lock holds. See D3 rationale above.
   186	        "doc" => "article",
   187	        _ => return Err(EngineError::Storage),
   188	    })
   189	}
   190	```
   191	
   192	(no allocator pressure; returns `&'static str`; used at both
   193	writer sites in D7.)
   194	
   195	## D4 — NOT NULL + migration strategy
   196	
   197	vec0 virtual tables in sqlite-vec `=0.1.7` (this repo's pin)
   198	support neither `ALTER TABLE ... ADD COLUMN` (a SQLite-level
   199	rule for virtual tables — https://www.sqlite.org/vtab.html) nor
   200	`ALTER TABLE ... RENAME` (rename support landed in sqlite-vec
   201	`v0.1.10-alpha.2`, April 2026, per the sqlite-vec release
   202	history). The migration is therefore a `DROP TABLE` + recreate
   203	under the same name, with the row population rebuilt from
   204	canonical state via the existing rebuild driver — not the
   205	staging-table + RENAME shape originally drafted.
   206	
   207	**Decision: land NOT NULL constraints from the start. The
   208	migration is a single writer-envelope rebuild — DROP the old
   209	`vector_default`, CREATE it again with the new schema under the
   210	same name, then repopulate via the existing
   211	`Engine::rebuild_vec0` / `rebuild_shadow_state` path
   212	(`RebuildKind::Vec0`). The writer enforces non-nullability from
   213	commit zero.**
   214	
   215	Schema versioning is owned by the engine's real migration
   216	framework: `migrate_with_event_sink(...)` at
   217	`src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:1238`, gated by
   218	`PRAGMA user_version` (probed at `lib.rs:2071-2072` for the
   219	`dump_schema` surface and at `lib.rs:2691` for the open-time
   220	sanity check). The new vec0 schema lands as a new
   221	`fathomdb_schema::Migration` step appended to the existing
   222	migration array passed into `open_with_migrations`
   223	(`lib.rs:1119-1131`); `migrate_with_event_sink` bumps
   224	`PRAGMA user_version` on commit and gates re-entry on the same
   225	sentinel, so re-opens are naturally idempotent. The previously
   226	proposed `operational_mutations` schema stamp is **not** the
   227	schema-version owner — that collection is excise audit rows
   228	(`lib.rs:2217-2221`) — and is dropped from the design.
   229	
   230	Migration step (Pack 1):
   231	
   232	```sql
   233	-- Step body, executed by migrate_with_event_sink at lib.rs:1238.
   234	-- Runs inside the migration framework's transaction envelope.
   235	DROP TABLE vector_default;
   236	CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE vector_default USING vec0(
   237	  embedding float[<dim>],
   238	  embedding_bin bit[<dim>],
   239	  source_type TEXT partition key,
   240	  kind TEXT,
   241	  created_at INTEGER
   242	);
   243	```
   244	
   245	Repopulation: deliberately not done by `INSERT ... SELECT` from
   246	the old vec0 (the old table is dropped above and the new one
   247	has zero rows). Instead, after the migration commits, the open
   248	path invokes the existing vec0 rebuild driver,
   249	`Engine::rebuild_vec0` (`lib.rs:1947`), which calls
   250	`run_rebuild` -> `rebuild_shadow_state` with `RebuildKind::Vec0`
   251	(`lib.rs:2234-2289`). That driver already knows how to:
   252	
   253	- Truncate the (newly-created, empty) `vector_default` and
   254	  `_fathomdb_vector_rows` shadow tables (no-op on first pass
   255	  but kept for the contract — see `lib.rs:2265-2270`).
   256	- Re-derive rows from `canonical_nodes` via the standard
   257	  projection pipeline, which writes through the Pack 1 writer
   258	  in D5 and therefore lands `embedding_bin`, `source_type`,
   259	  `kind`, `created_at` correctly on every row.
   260	
   261	The whole sequence runs under the engine's existing
   262	single-writer envelope: `migrate_with_event_sink` holds the
   263	writer for the DDL step, and `run_rebuild` re-acquires the
   264	writer transaction (`lib.rs:2257-2259`) immediately after.
   265	There is no window in which a reader can observe a partially
   266	rebuilt `vector_default`, because the engine does not advertise
   267	itself as open until `open_with_migrations` returns
   268	(`lib.rs:1238-1255`).
   269	
   270	NOT NULL enforcement:

